post_text: Excellent defensive work by our girls' soccer team against an undefeated Valley View team. Goal keeper Cadence Crocker had 22 saves. Seniors Melia Sergent and Jenna Horvath directed from the back. This was a hard fought game and everyone did great!

post_text:
Though Gov. DeWine has stated he intends to have students back in the classroom in the fall, the district has not received detailed guidance for the next school year (start date-August 18, 2020) from state officials.

At this time, we are currently gathering information and feedback from our staff, students, and parents in order to develop possible options. We will use the information collected from this survey and others to help guide our planning for the future which could include, depending on state guidelines and parameters, several possibilities such as in-person, remote learning, or a blend of remote and in-person learning, for the 2020-2021 school year.

Please answer these questions no later than June 11 using the information you have available today. We realize information continues to change daily, and your answers may shift as more information becomes available.

https://forms.gle/qaJhigBYsryWrGDY6

FHS students to participate in annual student art show:

Miamisburg Art Gallery, 16 N. Main St., Miamisburg, will host its 29th annual student art show March 7 through 28. Franklin High School students will be showcasing their work along with students from Miamisburg, Carlisle, Valley View, Springboro, Waynesville, Monroe, Madison, and John Lazares Alternative School.

Gallery hours are extended during the show, and the opening reception is Saturday, March 7, Noon to 8 p.m. Each school also has a designated night; Franklin's is Wednesday, March 25, 5:30 to 8 p.m.

The gallery's hours are Sunday, 1 to 5 p.m.; Monday through Thursday, 5:30 to 8:00 p.m., and Fridays and Saturdays Noon to 8 p.m #FCSWildcatPride

post_text:
Students inducted into NTHS:

Warren County Career Center inducted 63 seniors, including eight whose home school is Franklin High School, into the National Technical Honor Society on Feb. 20. To qualify for induction, students must have a 3.5 GPA for three semesters during the two years at WCCC or its satellites, and no grade lower than a ‚ÄúC‚Äù at any time. Students must also meet attendance and behavioral guidelines and have no credit deficiencies toward obtaining a high school diploma. The Franklin students were, from left to right, Madison Woods, Dental Assisting; Emily Garner, Pre-Nursing; Reya Gast, Veterinary Science; Dylan Kindla, Information Technology; Madison Meadows, Legal Office Technology; Ben Buckingham, Heavy Equipment/Site Construction; Parker Crawford, Advanced Manufacturing & Robotics. Not pictured: Tyler Dishun, Project Lead The Way Pre-Engineering.

The Warren County Imagination Library is here! Franklin City Schools is excited to be a partner in this county-wide effort with the goal that Every Child Reads Every Day!

All Warren County children under five can have a FREE book mailed to THEM every month. Sign up now at www.imaginationlibrary.org

Warren County Imagination Library Founding Partners are Franklin-Springboro Public Library , Lebanon Public Library, Mary L. Cook Public Library, Mason Public Library, Salem Township Public Library, United Way of Warren County, and Warren County Foundation The five libraries have generously funded a three-year pilot in collaboration with the Ohio Governor‚Äôs Imagination Library and Dolly Parton's Imagination Library

Please sign up, share this post and join us in The Biggest Civic Engagement in Warren County History ‚Äì A Generational Change! Questions? Contact the Warren County Imagination Library at 513-934-1001 or info@warrencountyfoundation.org

Franklin established the Student Achievement Award in January 2001 to honor students who have demonstrated exceptional achievement in academics, community service, or character. Hundreds of students have been honored since the award's inception.

United Way of Warren County
January 28 at 4:13 PM ¬∑

On Friday, January 17, United Way of Warren County led a workforce development roundtable discussion with U.S. Senator Rob Portman, Kings Superintendent Tim Ackerman, and Fecon, Inc. The event was a highlight on the Warren County schools and business partnerships and the students success. In addition to the importance of the JOBSAct which will enable more up-skill training for the workforce. Students spotlighted include 2019 graduates: 1) Zach Layman of Kings High School (Kings Mills, Ohio), 2) Andrew Vandyke of Wayne-Local Schools, and 3) Rickey Tussey, of Franklin City Schools. These graduates are all in the apprenticeship program with FECON, with 2 of them getting the welding certificate through a customized welding program with Fecon & Warren County Career Center. Fantastic partnership!

It's a dark and stormy night, and dinner guests arrive to find that all is NOT well at Boddy Manor. In fact, the host is dead, but by whose hand?

A zany cast of colorful characters race the clock to find out "whodunit?" as Franklin High School Drama Club presents the madcap farce Clue on Feb. 7 and 8 at 7 p.m., and Feb. 9 at 2 p.m. The play is based on the cult classic film and the popular board game. #fcswildcatpride

Tickets are $10 for adults, $8 for seniors, and $5 for students and are available at fhsdrama.booktix.com/ or at the door.

All performances will be in the FHS McDade Auditorium, 750 E. 4th St., Franklin.

To encourage a ‚ÄúSmall-Town Christmas‚Äù atmosphere, the evening will include a decorating contest on Main Street. Downtown businesses and homeowners are invited to decorate their store(s) or home fronts to celebrate the holiday season and the beauty of our Main Street.

Congratulations to Emily Rudy, an educator at Franklin High School in Franklin, OH, was recently selected as a Claes Nobel Educator of Distinction by The National Society of High School Scholars (NSHSS). A role model to pupils, Emily was nominated by a student for outstanding dedication and commitment to excellence in the profession.

Each year student members of NSHSS are invited to nominate the educator who has made the most significant contribution to their academic career for the Claes Nobel Educator of Distinction award. This honor recognizes exemplary educators whose passion and devotion inspire their students to grow and develop as scholars, leaders and citizens. #FCSWildcatPride

post_text:
Franklin High School plans Veterans Day Assembly

Franklin High School will hold its annual Veterans Day assembly on Thursday, Nov. 7, at 9 a.m.

All area veterans and their families are invited and encouraged to attend the event, which will be in the FHS auditorium. The morning will include vocal and instrumental music, readings, and recognition of those who have served. The keynote speaker is Franklin Township Trustee Matthew M. Jennings, Technical Sergeant, US Air Force, FHS Class of '03.

Those with questions should call Zach Katris at Franklin High School, (937) 743-8611, ext. 1256.

Community members who plan to attend should arrive before 8:45 a.m. for advanced seating. A brief reception will be held in the high school media center for veterans and their families following the ceremony. Franklin High School is at 750 E. 4th St., Franklin.

FHS to present The Lion, the Witch, and the Wardrobe

Four children open the door of an old wardrobe and wander into the magical land of Narnia, where they encounter the great lion Aslan, and become entangled in his struggle with the White Witch.

Hear the story of the children's adventures in Narnia as Franklin High School presents The Lion, The Witch, and The Wardrobe. The show, which is dramatized by Joseph Robinette from the story by C.S. Lewis, will be presented on Friday and Saturday, Nov. 1 and 2 at 7 p.m., and Sunday, Nov. 3 at 2 p.m. Tickets are $10 adults, $8 for seniors, and $5 for students. They will be available at the door or at fhsdrama.booktix.com

On Thurs, Oct. 31, a complimentary lunch (11 a.m.) and senior citizens performance (Noon) will be presented. Call Franklin High School to make a reservation for this special performance, (937) 743-8610. RSVPs for this performance are needed by 3 p.m. on Tuesday, Oct. 29.

Franklin High School is at 750 E. 4th St., Franklin.

post_text:
ANTHONY WAYNE CHILI COOK-OFF RULES
Tuesday, October 15, 2019

**All chili must be prepared at home and brought to school in a Crockpot.**
1. Each participant must produce one large Crockpot of the chili of their choice.
2. Each participant must supply all toppings and sides that go with their chili.
3. All chili entries must be brought to school by 4:30pm.
4. Each chili entry will be judged in four categories: taste, consistency, aroma, and color.
5. Each chili entry will be assigned a number and judging will be accomplished through a blind-taste test.
6. For the popular vote, the PTO will provide $1.00 bowls and spoons to the general public so they can sample the chili entries.
7. Prizes will be awarded for 1st, 2nd, and 3rd place, as well as a popular vote.
8. Winners will be announced at approximately 7:10pm and prizes awarded.
9. Each participant is responsible for clean-up of their space at the end of the cook-off.
GOOD LUCK AND HAPPY COOKING!

post_text: The work continues for FJHS! Students studied in small groups comparing samples from the 2007 "Cold Case" to present day. They tested the pH and made observations, studied macro-invertebrates and how they indicate water quality while the final group learned about the City of Franklin Public Works Dept. They found our creek water to be very healthy today! But the case they studied had possible pollutants... stay tuned! #FCSWildcatPride

Graduate Services came and met with the FHS Class of 2020 about ordering their Caps and Gowns, Announcements, and other graduate items/apparel on Monday September 16th. Please make sure you ask your student about this information. Graduate Services will be back at FHS on Tuesday October 1st to pick up orders at lunch. If your student attends the WCCC, Graduate Services will meet with students there on Thursday October 24th, and will be back at the WCCC to pick-up orders during lunch on November 6th and November 13th. If by chance the information packets do not make it home, we have additional in the FHS Main Office.

Information to Contact Graduate Services Directly:

(513)272-5890 or www.graduateserviceinc.com

Our sales representative is Jamie Pruitt
